## Code Style Rules
- Always use optional chaining (?.) and nullish coalescing (??) when accessing nested object properties
- All user-facing data must be treated as potentially undefined on first render
- Use `useMemo` and `useCallback` only with proper dependency arrays
- Prefer server components; use "use client" only when necessary
- Always type props and return values explicitly — no implicit `any`
- Use loading/error states for all async data fetching

## Domain Knowledge
- Users have profiles with: badges (earned[], locked[]), progress, points, rank, solved challenges
- Badges are awarded on specific events (e.g. first blood, streak, completing a path)
- Challenges have: difficulty (Easy/Medium/Hard/Insane), category (SQLi, XSS, SSRF, etc.), points, hints, flags
- Labs are isolated environments users can start/stop
- Leaderboards are ranked by points, with optional filters (weekly, monthly, all-time)

## When Fixing Bugs
- Always check for undefined/null before accessing nested properties
- Check if the TypeScript type matches the actual runtime data shape
- If mock data is used, ensure it fully matches the TypeScript interface
- Mention both the quick fix and the root cause

## When Adding Features
- Follow existing file/folder naming conventions
- Reuse existing components before creating new ones
- Keep mock data and real API calls clearly separated
- Always consider mobile responsiveness

## What to Avoid
- Never use `any` type without explanation
- Never access nested properties without null checks
- Never mix server and client component patterns incorrectly
- Do not install new dependencies without asking first